	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Re: Pax Romana</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#a62a2a" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Haritrium shook his head in disgust. “No, no, no!&quot; He grabbed the wooden handles over his assistant's grip and shoved the hide-skin covered bellows in and out of the blow hole with a stong and solid motion. &quot;Like this. The bellows have to remain moving at a steady pace. This helps the fire to remain hot and yet even throughout the coal bed.” The younger man manning the accordian bellows bowed his head apologetically and wiped the grimy sweat from his ruddy brow.<br />
<br />
“Sorry, Lord Haritrium.”<br />
<br />
Already forgetting the incident, Haritrium grunted and turned his attention back to his forge. <i>“How am I supposed to improve on the bronze armor?” </i> he mused, shuffling the embers around the hearth, skimming the ashen ones from the top and sliding them to the detritus trough by his legs. He sighed. <i>“Why did I take this job? It seemed like a great idea; find a way to improve on the armor our soldiers wear, and be paid my weight in gold.”</i> He glanced down to his barrel shaped waist and grinned.<br />
<br />
A moment later he found himself scowling. <i>“Vulcan damn it! Too much copper and the bronze becomes soft; too much tin and the bronze become brittle.” </i> He slid the stone crucible across the coals to the leeward side of the forge, allowing the molten bronze to bleed off some of its heat. <i>“So far the best I’ve been able to do is completely heat the mixture of both metals, allowing a better flow, resulting in a purer alloy.” </i> Once it cooled and the molten bronze began to crust over, Haritrium slid the thick wooden cradle around the stone's neck, and lifted.<br />
<br />
“Veritus, enough with the forge,” the smith demanded. Leaving the bellows, Veritus quickly grabbed a thick leather pad, doused it with water, and ran to help steady Haritrium and his load. Together, the two men brought the crucible over to the spear and sword molds, carefully upended, and allowed the rich bronze to pour into the precarved forms of the empire's future arms.<br />
<br />
The hot metal hissed and popped as it ran over the cooler stone of the mold, running fast through the channels as it filled the weapon outlines. When finished, the two men lowered the now empty container and instead, lifted the mold's cover off the sawhorses where it sat; carefully placing it on top of the other half and its molten bronze weaponry. Once the wooden pegs lined up, the top was lowered and then rested flush.<br />
<br />
Quickly Haritrium searched the edges where the molds met, looking for any sign of leaking bronze. Satisfied there was none, he motioned to Veritus. “Ok boy. Seal the mold, band it tight, and then you're free to go home for the night. Get some rest and I'll see you on the morrow past 7:00.”<br />
<br />
“Yes, Lord Haritrium.”<br />
<br />
The forge master turned away from his apprentice and retreated to his workbench. Covered in bits of bronze, brass, copper, tin, gold, silver, and other metal chuncks, there seemed little room for anything else, save one. Haritrium sat down absently, his attention taken with the raw and untouched stone taking the greater part of his bench's mid section. The rock was large and deeply flecked with the telltale sign of dunnish grey iron deposits. Huge gouges and chisel marks etched its surface.<br />
<br />
<i>“Yes, this is the way,” </i> he thought. <i>“Harder and denser than tin. Iron would make a better tool and weapon for Lord Ceaser.” </i> Grabbing a wooden mallet, he rapped the ferrous stone in frustration. <i>“But how am I to harvest the iron properly?! It’s too brittle while untreated to be chipped off its native rock. There is never enough found in large quantities virgin and unmixed with other metals. I don’t have enough men at my disposal to help me in this matter.”</i><br />
<br />
Haritrium heard Veritus call out goodbye and the door to the forge close, leaving the heavy set smith alone in his shop; the cooling forge still throwing off enough heat to raise sweat across his brow. <i>“Anyone with any skills and brains is being wooed away from smithing! For what? To studying the growing idea of numbers. Bah! As if numbers can protect our soldiers in the field! As if numbers have any secret that we can use! 1, 2, 3, 4, that’s numbers! Why they waste their time on such a foolishness is ludicrous! Especially in this time when the empire needs everyone everywhere pitching in and helping while the barbarians are stealing our people away!” </i> Again, Haritrium had to wipe the sweat from his forehead, scowling as he did so. He glanced back, just to assure himself that the forge was not still being stoked by some entitiy or spirit.<br />
<br />
<i>“Veritus had the fire burning well tonight, Vulcan himself would be pleased.&quot;</i> Another swab of offending sweat was toweled away with his sodden sleeve. <i>&quot;Ah, Lord of Smiths, I ask you now, if there’s something I’m over looking, please give me a sign.”</i> Haritrium bowed his head, offering a rapid prayer to his patron god. Wriggling his face, he could feel the beads of sweat running across his cheeks and down his nose.<br />
<br />
At his prayer’s end, he wiped the moisture from his face with a disgusted snarl. “By the gods,” he swore, “if it was any hotter in here, I could set my skin ablaze! I could melt wood! The thrice be-damned forge stones would sweat!”<br />
<br />
Shaking damp hair from his eyes, Haritrium got up abruptly to leave for the night when he stopped. Looking down, he glanced at his table. The table where the vexing iron filled rock had been nagging him for weeks. He began to smile. It started as a giggle, then a snort, then a laugh, and finally a bellowing, rocking, deep blowing, guffaw; the mirth burbling out of his expanded waist, filling the forge with its sound and bringing tears to his eyes.<br />
<br />
“The <b>stone </b> itself would <b>sweat</b>!” he cried out, laughing the entire time. Running to the door, Haritrium grabbed his faded red cloak, grinned once more at the iron ore on his desk, and dashed out into the night; running down the road to where Veritus lived, hoping that his apprentice hadn’t yet gotten ready for bed.<br />
<br />
<i>&quot;No, the night was still young, and iron will flow.&quot; </i> Haritrium's teeth flashed in the moonlight.<br />
<br />
And flowing iron meant gold. Gold in the smith's pocket. <i>“Hail Ceaser,” </i> he muttered, <i>“and hail me and my riches.” </i> Haritrium ran faster into the night, running towards his apprentice and his destiny.</div>
